ction and commentary by a specialist in the field--the collection illustrates the religious cycles, rituals, and experiences that gave meaning to medieval Christian individuals and communities.This volume of Princeton Readings in Religions assembles sources reflecting different genres, regions, and styles, including prayer books, chronicles, diaries, liturgical books, sermons, hagiography, and handbooks for the laity and clergy. The texts represent the practices through which Christians conducted their individual, family, and community lives, and explores such life-cycle events as birth, confirmation, marriage, sickness, death, and burial. The texts also document religious practices related to themes of work, parish life, and devotions, as well as power and authority. Enriched by expert analysis and suggestions for further reading, Medieval Christianity in Practice gives students and general readers alike the necessary background and foundations for an appreciation of the creativity and multiplicity of medieval Christian religious culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChristian lifexHistoryyMiddle Ages, 600-1500vSources. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / History.2bisacsh  aAdalbert of Prague.  aBenedict of Nursia.  aBirgitta of Sweden.  aCaesarius of Heisterbach.  aCafaggiolo.  aEleanor of Aquitaine.  aEleanor of Provence.  aExeter Pontifical.  aFerdinand of Aragon.  aGandersheim.  aGelasian Sacramentary.  aGrandmontains.  aGuicciardini, Gostanza.  aHelen of Hungary.  aIbn Jubayr.  aIda of Louvain.  aJerome.  aKempe, Margery.  aLacnunga.  aLe Goff, Jacques.  aLollardy.  aNicholas of Lyre.  aOberweimar, Saxony.  aPaschasius Radbertus.  aabsolution.  aadventus novi episcopi.  aagriculture.  aamulets.  aanointing rituals.  abarbatoria.  abeghards.  abooks o